"""
IT Helpdesk / Customer Support Ticket Dataset for ResolveX.

Based on real-world IT helpdesk and customer support datasets from Kaggle
(e.g., "IT Helpdesk Dataset", "Customer Support Ticket Dataset").

Dataset fields:
  - title: Short summary of the issue
  - description: Detailed description of the problem reported by the user
  - category: Classification label (technical, billing, account, network, software, hardware)
  - resolution: Step-by-step resolution or response text

Usage in the system:
  - Training/Evaluating the classification model for auto-categorization
  - Building the FAISS similarity search index of solved tickets
  - Generating AI-powered recommendations and troubleshooting suggestions for users

Source Reference: Kaggle IT Helpdesk / Customer Support Ticket datasets
  - https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/suraj520/customer-support-ticket-dataset
  - https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/adisongoh/it-helpdesk-dataset
"""

SOLVED_TICKETS = [
    # ─── TECHNICAL ───
    {"title": "Computer keeps freezing randomly", "description": "My desktop computer freezes every 30 minutes and I have to force restart it. It started happening after a Windows update.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "This is likely caused by a driver incompatibility after the Windows update. Steps to resolve: 1) Open Device Manager and check for yellow warning icons. 2) Right-click the problematic driver and select 'Update driver'. 3) If the issue persists, go to Settings > Update & Security > View update history > Uninstall updates, and remove the latest update. 4) Run 'sfc /scannow' in Command Prompt as Administrator to repair system files. 5) Check Event Viewer for critical errors under Windows Logs > System."},
    {"title": "Blue screen of death BSOD error", "description": "Getting BSOD with error code IRQL_NOT_LESS_OR_EQUAL. Happens when opening multiple applications.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "IRQL_NOT_LESS_OR_EQUAL typically indicates a RAM or driver issue. Steps: 1) Run Windows Memory Diagnostic tool (mdsched.exe). 2) Update all drivers, especially graphics and chipset drivers. 3) Run 'chkdsk /f /r' to check for disk errors. 4) If you recently installed new RAM, remove it and test. 5) Boot in Safe Mode to check if the issue persists. 6) Check minidump files in C:\\Windows\\Minidump for the exact failing driver."},
    {"title": "Laptop not charging when plugged in", "description": "My laptop shows plugged in but not charging. The battery is stuck at 45% and won't increase.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Try these steps: 1) Shut down the laptop completely, unplug the charger, remove the battery (if removable), hold the power button for 30 seconds, then reassemble. 2) Check if the charger is the correct wattage for your laptop. 3) Update the battery driver: Device Manager > Batteries > Microsoft ACPI-Compliant Control Method Battery > Uninstall > Restart. 4) Check power settings: Control Panel > Power Options > Change plan settings > Reset to default. 5) If the battery is older than 2-3 years, it may need replacement."},
    {"title": "Keyboard keys not responding", "description": "Several keys on my keyboard stopped working. The letters Q, W, and E do not register when pressed.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Steps to troubleshoot: 1) Test with an external USB keyboard to rule out software issues. 2) Check if Filter Keys is enabled: Settings > Accessibility > Keyboard > Turn off Filter Keys. 3) Update keyboard driver in Device Manager. 4) For laptops, the ribbon cable may be loose - this requires professional service. 5) Try the on-screen keyboard as a temporary solution (Win + Ctrl + O). 6) If it's a mechanical keyboard, the specific switches may need replacement."},
    {"title": "Computer running extremely slow", "description": "My PC takes 10 minutes to boot and programs are very slow to open. It used to be fast.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Performance optimization steps: 1) Open Task Manager (Ctrl+Shift+Esc) and check Startup tab - disable unnecessary startup programs. 2) Run Disk Cleanup (cleanmgr) to free up space. 3) Check for malware: run Windows Defender full scan. 4) Ensure at least 15% of your disk is free. 5) Consider upgrading to an SSD if using an HDD. 6) Increase virtual memory: System Properties > Advanced > Performance Settings > Advanced > Virtual Memory. 7) Run 'msconfig' and ensure Normal startup is selected."},
    {"title": "Monitor displaying no signal", "description": "My monitor says no signal detected even though the computer is on and the cable is connected.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Troubleshooting steps: 1) Check that the cable (HDMI/DP/VGA) is firmly connected at both ends. 2) Try a different cable. 3) Try a different port on the graphics card. 4) If you have integrated graphics, try connecting to the motherboard port. 5) Remove and reseat the graphics card. 6) Try the monitor with another computer. 7) Reset the monitor to factory settings using its built-in menu. 8) Clear CMOS by removing the motherboard battery for 30 seconds."},
    {"title": "Printer not connecting to computer", "description": "My printer is not showing up when I try to print. It was working fine yesterday.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Steps to fix: 1) Restart both the printer and computer. 2) Check USB/network connection. 3) Go to Settings > Devices > Printers & Scanners > Add a printer. 4) Run the Printer troubleshooter: Settings > Update & Security > Troubleshoot > Printer. 5) Restart Print Spooler service: Open Services (services.msc), find Print Spooler, right-click > Restart. 6) Delete and re-add the printer. 7) Download the latest driver from the manufacturer's website."},
    {"title": "USB ports not recognizing devices", "description": "None of the USB ports on my laptop recognize any device. Flash drives and peripherals are not detected.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Try these solutions: 1) Restart the computer. 2) In Device Manager, expand Universal Serial Bus controllers, right-click each USB Root Hub > Properties > Power Management > Uncheck 'Allow the computer to turn off this device'. 3) Uninstall all USB controllers in Device Manager and restart. 4) Update chipset drivers from the manufacturer. 5) Check BIOS settings to ensure USB is enabled. 6) Try booting from a USB drive to test if ports work at hardware level."},
    {"title": "Webcam not working in video calls", "description": "My built-in webcam shows a black screen in Zoom and Teams. Other apps can't access it either.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Steps: 1) Check if there's a physical privacy shutter or switch on your laptop. 2) Check camera permissions: Settings > Privacy > Camera > Ensure apps have access. 3) Update camera driver in Device Manager. 4) Check if another app is using the camera (close all apps and retry). 5) Run the Hardware troubleshooter. 6) In Device Manager, right-click the camera > Uninstall device > Restart. 7) Check antivirus settings that may block camera access."},
    {"title": "Audio crackling and distortion", "description": "My computer audio has crackling and popping sounds through both speakers and headphones.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Fix audio issues: 1) Right-click the speaker icon > Sound settings > Output > ensure correct device is selected. 2) Update audio driver in Device Manager. 3) Disable audio enhancements: Sound settings > Device Properties > Additional device properties > Enhancements > Disable all. 4) Change audio format: Advanced tab > Change to 24-bit 48000Hz. 5) Disable Exclusive Mode in the Advanced tab. 6) Check for DPC latency using LatencyMon tool. 7) Try reinstalling the audio driver from the manufacturer."},

    # ─── NETWORK ───
    {"title": "WiFi keeps disconnecting frequently", "description": "My WiFi connection drops every few minutes and I have to reconnect. This happens on my laptop but not on my phone.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Steps to fix WiFi disconnection: 1) Update WiFi adapter driver from Device Manager. 2) Disable WiFi power saving: Device Manager > Network adapters > WiFi adapter > Properties > Power Management > Uncheck 'Allow the computer to turn off this device'. 3) Forget the network and reconnect. 4) Run network troubleshooter: Settings > Network > Network troubleshooter. 5) Reset network settings: Settings > Network > Network reset. 6) Change WiFi band from 5GHz to 2.4GHz or vice versa in router settings."},
    {"title": "Cannot connect to VPN", "description": "Getting error 'VPN connection failed' when trying to connect to the company VPN. Was working last week.", "category": "network", "resolution": "VPN troubleshooting: 1) Restart your computer and router. 2) Check if your internet connection is stable without VPN. 3) Verify VPN credentials haven't expired - contact IT for password reset if needed. 4) Try different VPN protocols (IKEv2, OpenVPN, L2TP). 5) Disable firewall temporarily to test. 6) Flush DNS: Run 'ipconfig /flushdns' in Command Prompt. 7) Reinstall the VPN client. 8) If using split tunneling, check routing table with 'route print'."},
    {"title": "Internet connected but no pages loading", "description": "WiFi shows connected with full bars but no website loads. Getting DNS_PROBE_FINISHED_NO_INTERNET error.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Steps to resolve: 1) Open Command Prompt as Admin and run these commands in order: 'ipconfig /release', 'ipconfig /flushdns', 'ipconfig /renew'. 2) Change DNS to Google DNS: Settings > Network > Change adapter options > Properties > IPv4 > Use 8.8.8.8 and 8.8.4.4. 3) Reset Winsock: Run 'netsh winsock reset' as Admin. 4) Disable proxy: Settings > Network > Proxy > Turn off manual proxy. 5) Try a different browser. 6) Check if the issue persists in Safe Mode with Networking."},
    {"title": "Network drive not accessible", "description": "Cannot access the shared network drive. Getting 'Windows cannot access \\\\server\\share' error.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Fix network drive access: 1) Ensure you're connected to the correct network/VPN. 2) Try accessing by IP instead of hostname: \\\\192.168.x.x\\share. 3) Re-enter credentials: Control Panel > Credential Manager > Windows Credentials > Remove old entries. 4) Enable SMB: Control Panel > Programs > Turn Windows features on > SMB 1.0/CIFS. 5) Check firewall isn't blocking file sharing. 6) Run 'net use' to see current connections, then 'net use * /delete' to clear them. 7) Contact your network admin to verify your access permissions."},
    {"title": "Slow network speed on office computer", "description": "My download speed is very slow on the office network. Speed tests show 5 Mbps when it should be 100 Mbps.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Diagnose slow network: 1) Test with a wired connection if currently on WiFi. 2) Check if other devices have the same issue. 3) In Device Manager, update network adapter driver. 4) Check adapter speed: Network adapter properties > Speed & Duplex > ensure set to Auto Negotiation. 5) Disable Large Send Offload in adapter properties. 6) Check for bandwidth-heavy background processes in Task Manager > Network. 7) Try a different Ethernet cable (Cat5e or Cat6). 8) Contact network admin to check switch port configuration."},
    {"title": "Email client not sending emails", "description": "Outlook is receiving emails but cannot send any. Getting error 'Send/Receive reported error 0x800CCC0E'.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Fix Outlook sending issues: 1) Check SMTP server settings: File > Account Settings > Change > Outgoing mail server. 2) Ensure SMTP port is correct (587 for TLS, 465 for SSL). 3) Enable SMTP authentication: More Settings > Outgoing Server > check 'My outgoing server requires authentication'. 4) Temporarily disable antivirus email scanning. 5) Create a new Outlook profile: Control Panel > Mail > Show Profiles > Add. 6) Try using Outlook in Safe Mode: Run 'outlook.exe /safe'. 7) Check if your ISP blocks port 25."},
    {"title": "Cannot connect to remote desktop", "description": "Remote Desktop Connection fails with 'Remote Desktop can't connect to the remote computer'. I need to access my work PC.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Remote Desktop fixes: 1) Verify the remote PC is powered on. 2) Check if Remote Desktop is enabled on the target: Settings > System > Remote Desktop > Enable. 3) Ensure you're using the correct IP/hostname. 4) Check firewall: Allow 'Remote Desktop' through Windows Firewall. 5) Verify you're on the same network or VPN. 6) Try specifying the port: computer:3389. 7) Check if NLA (Network Level Authentication) is causing issues - try disabling it temporarily. 8) Restart Remote Desktop Services on the target machine."},

    # ─── SOFTWARE ───
    {"title": "Microsoft Office not activating", "description": "After reinstalling Windows, Microsoft Office shows 'Product Activation Required'. I have a valid license key.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Activate Office: 1) Go to File > Account > Change Product Key and enter your key. 2) If using Microsoft 365, sign in with your Microsoft account. 3) Run the Office activation troubleshooter from Microsoft support. 4) Try command-line activation: Open Command Prompt as Admin, navigate to Office folder (C:\\Program Files\\Microsoft Office\\Office16), run 'cscript ospp.vbs /act'. 5) Clear existing activation: 'cscript ospp.vbs /unpkey:XXXXX' (last 5 digits of current key). 6) If volume license, check with your IT department for KMS server."},
    {"title": "Application crashes on startup", "description": "A specific application crashes immediately when I try to open it. It shows 'Application has stopped working' error.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Troubleshoot application crashes: 1) Run the application as Administrator (right-click > Run as administrator). 2) Check for pending Windows updates. 3) Update the application to the latest version. 4) Run in compatibility mode: Right-click app > Properties > Compatibility > Run in compatibility mode for Windows 8/10. 5) Reinstall the application after fully uninstalling (including AppData folders). 6) Check Event Viewer > Windows Logs > Application for detailed error info. 7) Install/repair Visual C++ Redistributables and .NET Framework. 8) Disable antivirus temporarily to test."},
    {"title": "Cannot install software - access denied", "description": "Getting 'Access Denied' error when trying to install new software on my work computer.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Steps to resolve: 1) Right-click the installer and select 'Run as administrator'. 2) If that doesn't work, your organization may restrict software installations - contact your IT admin. 3) Check if User Account Control (UAC) is blocking: Control Panel > User Accounts > Change UAC settings. 4) Try running the installer from Command Prompt as Admin. 5) Check Group Policy restrictions: Run 'gpedit.msc' > Computer Configuration > Windows Settings > Security Settings > Software Restriction Policies. 6) If it's a portable application, try running it from a user-writable directory."},
    {"title": "Excel file corrupted and won't open", "description": "An important Excel spreadsheet shows 'The file is corrupt and cannot be opened' error. I need this file urgently.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Recover corrupted Excel file: 1) Try Open and Repair: Open Excel > File > Open > Browse to file > Click the dropdown arrow on Open button > Select 'Open and Repair'. 2) Try opening in Safe Mode: Hold Ctrl while opening Excel. 3) Check for auto-recover files: File > Info > Manage Workbook > Recover Unsaved Workbooks. 4) Look in the temp folder: %temp% for temporary Excel files. 5) Change the file extension from .xlsx to .zip, extract, and check if xl/worksheets/sheet1.xml is readable. 6) Try opening in Google Sheets or LibreOffice Calc. 7) Use a file recovery tool as last resort."},
    {"title": "Software license expired notification", "description": "Getting a notification that my software license has expired. I believe it should still be valid.", "category": "software", "resolution": "License resolution steps: 1) Check the license expiration date in the software's About/License section. 2) Verify your license type (subscription vs perpetual). 3) If subscription, check payment status in your account portal. 4) Try deactivating and reactivating the license. 5) Clear license cache: delete license files from AppData (location varies by software). 6) Contact your IT department to verify license allocation. 7) If you have the license key, try re-entering it. 8) Contact the software vendor's support with your order/license details."},
    {"title": "Browser extensions causing crashes", "description": "Chrome keeps crashing and I suspect it's due to extensions. Multiple tabs freeze simultaneously.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Fix browser extension issues: 1) Open Chrome in Safe Mode: launch with '--disable-extensions' flag. 2) If Chrome works fine, enable extensions one by one to find the culprit. 3) Go to chrome://extensions and disable all, then re-enable selectively. 4) Clear browser cache and cookies. 5) Reset Chrome: Settings > Reset settings > Restore settings to their original defaults. 6) Check for conflicting extensions (multiple ad blockers, VPN extensions). 7) Update Chrome to the latest version. 8) Check if the issue occurs in a new Chrome profile."},
    {"title": "Antivirus blocking legitimate application", "description": "My antivirus keeps quarantining a work application that I know is safe. It marks it as a threat every time I restore it.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Add antivirus exception: 1) Open your antivirus program. 2) Go to Settings/Preferences > Exclusions/Exceptions. 3) Add the application's installation folder to the exclusion list. 4) Also add the executable file path specifically. 5) In Windows Defender: Settings > Update & Security > Windows Security > Virus & threat protection > Manage settings > Exclusions > Add. 6) Restore the quarantined file after adding the exclusion. 7) Report the false positive to the antivirus vendor. 8) If using enterprise antivirus, contact IT to add a company-wide exclusion."},

    # ─── BILLING ───
    {"title": "Charged twice for subscription", "description": "I was charged twice this month for my software subscription. My bank statement shows two identical charges.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Steps to resolve double charge: 1) Take a screenshot of both charges from your bank statement. 2) Log into your account portal and check payment/billing history. 3) Contact billing support with the transaction IDs of both charges. 4) If you paid through different methods, check if one was an old auto-renewal. 5) Request a refund for the duplicate charge - most companies process this within 5-7 business days. 6) Check if you have multiple accounts with the same provider. 7) Keep documentation of all communication for reference."},
    {"title": "Cannot update payment method", "description": "The portal won't let me update my credit card. Getting error when trying to save new payment information.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Fix payment update issues: 1) Clear browser cache and cookies, then retry. 2) Try a different browser (sometimes payment forms have compatibility issues). 3) Ensure the card details are correct: number, expiration date, CVV, and billing address. 4) Check if your card is enabled for online transactions. 5) Disable browser extensions (especially ad blockers) that might interfere. 6) Try using incognito/private browsing mode. 7) If using a virtual card, some systems don't accept them. 8) Contact billing support to update payment details manually through their system."},
    {"title": "Refund not received after cancellation", "description": "I cancelled my subscription 2 weeks ago and was promised a refund, but it hasn't appeared in my account yet.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Refund tracking steps: 1) Check your original cancellation confirmation email for the refund timeline. 2) Log into your account to verify cancellation status. 3) Refunds typically take 5-10 business days to process, but can take up to 30 days depending on the payment method. 4) Check if the refund went to the original payment method. 5) Contact your bank to check for pending credits. 6) If using PayPal, check your PayPal account for the refund. 7) Contact billing support with your cancellation confirmation number. 8) If it's been more than 30 days, file a dispute with your bank/credit card company."},
    {"title": "Invoice shows wrong amount", "description": "My latest invoice shows a higher amount than what my subscription plan costs. There are charges I don't recognize.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Resolve invoice discrepancy: 1) Review the invoice line by line to identify unexpected charges. 2) Check if there were usage-based charges (overage, additional users, storage). 3) Look for prorated charges if you upgraded mid-cycle. 4) Check for tax additions that may not have been included before. 5) Verify your current subscription plan and pricing in account settings. 6) Contact billing support with the invoice number and specific line items in question. 7) Request an itemized billing statement if not already provided."},
    {"title": "Auto-renewal charged after cancellation", "description": "I cancelled my subscription last month but was still charged for auto-renewal this month.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Steps for wrongful auto-renewal charge: 1) Check the effective date of your cancellation - some cancellations take effect at the end of the billing cycle. 2) Look for cancellation confirmation email with the effective end date. 3) Log into your account to verify current subscription status. 4) Contact billing support immediately with proof of cancellation. 5) Request an immediate refund for the unauthorized charge. 6) If not resolved, file a chargeback with your credit card company. 7) Keep all emails and screenshots as documentation."},
    {"title": "Need to downgrade subscription plan", "description": "I want to downgrade my plan but the option is greyed out. I only need the basic features now.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Downgrade assistance: 1) Check if you're in a contract period that prevents downgrades. 2) Some plans require waiting until the end of the current billing cycle to downgrade. 3) Go to Account Settings > Subscription > Change Plan. 4) If the option is unavailable, contact billing support to request a manual downgrade. 5) Note: downgrading may result in loss of certain features or data. 6) Ask about prorated credits for the remaining period. 7) Consider cancelling and re-subscribing to the lower plan if direct downgrade isn't possible."},

    # ─── ACCOUNT ───
    {"title": "Cannot reset password", "description": "The password reset email never arrives. I've checked spam folder and tried multiple times.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Password reset troubleshooting: 1) Verify you're using the correct email address associated with your account. 2) Check spam/junk folders in your email. 3) Add the service's domain to your email whitelist. 4) Wait 15-30 minutes as some emails are delayed. 5) Try the 'Resend' option if available. 6) Clear browser cache and try from incognito mode. 7) If your email provider is blocking the reset email, try using a different recovery method (phone, security questions). 8) Contact support directly to manually reset your password with identity verification."},
    {"title": "Account locked after too many login attempts", "description": "My account got locked because I tried wrong passwords too many times. Now I can't log in at all.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Unlock your account: 1) Most accounts auto-unlock after 15-30 minutes. Wait and try again. 2) Use the 'Forgot Password' option to reset your password. 3) Check your email for an account unlock link. 4) If using a work account, contact your IT administrator to unlock it. 5) For Active Directory accounts, the admin can use 'Active Directory Users and Computers' to unlock. 6) Enable multi-factor authentication after regaining access to prevent unauthorized attempts. 7) Consider using a password manager to avoid forgotten passwords."},
    {"title": "Two-factor authentication not working", "description": "My 2FA codes from the authenticator app are not being accepted. I can't log into my account.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Fix 2FA issues: 1) Ensure your device's time is synced correctly: Settings > Date & Time > Set automatically. Time drift is the #1 cause of 2FA failures. 2) Try the next code that appears (codes change every 30 seconds). 3) Use backup codes if you saved them during setup. 4) If using SMS 2FA, check your phone's signal. 5) Try removing and re-adding the account in your authenticator app. 6) Contact support with your identity verification to disable 2FA temporarily. 7) After regaining access, reconfigure 2FA and save new backup codes securely."},
    {"title": "Profile information not updating", "description": "I changed my name and phone number in profile settings but the old information keeps showing up.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Fix profile update issues: 1) Clear your browser cache and refresh the page. 2) Log out and log back in after making changes. 3) Check if there's a 'Save' or 'Update' button you might have missed. 4) Try updating from a different browser or device. 5) Some systems have separate profiles (display name vs account name) - check all sections. 6) If using SSO (Single Sign-On), your profile may be synced from your identity provider (e.g., Active Directory). Contact your IT admin to update at the source. 7) Contact support if the issue persists."},
    {"title": "Need to merge duplicate accounts", "description": "I accidentally created two accounts with different email addresses. I want to merge them into one.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Account merge process: 1) Log into both accounts and note the email addresses and any data associated with each. 2) Most platforms don't have self-service merge - contact support. 3) When contacting support, provide both email addresses and proof of ownership. 4) Ask about data migration - ensure important data from the secondary account will be transferred. 5) Decide which account to keep as primary. 6) After merge, update any saved bookmarks or login credentials. 7) Some systems can't merge - in that case, manually transfer important data and close the duplicate account."},
    {"title": "Email notifications not being received", "description": "I'm not getting any email notifications from the system even though they're enabled in my settings.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Fix email notifications: 1) Check notification settings in your account - ensure they're toggled on for the types you want. 2) Check spam/junk folders. 3) Add the sender's domain to your email whitelist/safe senders list. 4) Verify the email address in your profile is correct and confirmed. 5) Check if your email provider has a 'Promotions' or 'Updates' tab where notifications might be filtered. 6) Try changing your notification email address temporarily. 7) Check if your organization's email server blocks certain external emails. 8) Contact support to reset your notification preferences."},
    {"title": "Unable to delete account", "description": "I want to delete my account but cannot find the option anywhere in the settings.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Account deletion steps: 1) Check Settings > Account > Privacy/Security for a 'Delete Account' option. 2) Some platforms require you to contact support for account deletion (GDPR/data protection requirement). 3) Before deletion, download any important data (look for 'Export Data' option). 4) Cancel any active subscriptions first. 5) Remove any linked payment methods. 6) Send a formal account deletion request to the platform's support/privacy email. 7) Under GDPR, companies must comply within 30 days. 8) After deletion, clear browser data and revoke any connected app permissions."},
    {"title": "Session keeps timing out too quickly", "description": "I keep getting logged out after just a few minutes of inactivity. It's very frustrating.", "category": "account", "resolution": "Session timeout solutions: 1) Check if 'Remember me' or 'Stay signed in' option is available at login. 2) Ensure cookies are enabled in your browser (Settings > Privacy > Cookies). 3) Check if your browser is set to clear cookies on exit. 4) Disable browser extensions that manage cookies or privacy. 5) The timeout may be set by your organization's security policy - contact IT admin. 6) Try a different browser to see if the issue persists. 7) Check if a VPN or proxy is causing session issues. 8) If using incognito mode, sessions won't persist - use normal browsing mode."},

    # ─── HARDWARE ───
    {"title": "Hard drive making clicking noises", "description": "My computer's hard drive is making clicking and grinding noises. It's getting louder over the past week.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "URGENT - Backup immediately: 1) A clicking hard drive often indicates imminent drive failure. Back up all important data NOW. 2) Use a tool like CrystalDiskInfo to check drive health (SMART status). 3) Do NOT run chkdsk or defragment - this can accelerate failure. 4) If the drive is still accessible, clone it to a new drive using Clonezilla or Macrium Reflect. 5) Replace the hard drive with an SSD for better reliability and performance. 6) If data is inaccessible, consider professional data recovery services. 7) For warranty claims, check the drive's warranty status on the manufacturer's website."},
    {"title": "Laptop screen flickering", "description": "My laptop screen flickers when I move the lid or when it's at certain angles. Sometimes it goes completely black.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "Screen flickering diagnosis: 1) If flickering changes with lid angle, it's likely a display cable issue (ribbon cable connecting screen to motherboard). 2) Update graphics drivers first to rule out software issues. 3) Connect an external monitor - if external display is fine, the issue is with the laptop screen/cable. 4) Check if the issue occurs in BIOS (restart and enter BIOS) - if yes, it's definitely hardware. 5) For cable issues, a technician needs to open the laptop and reseat/replace the display cable. 6) If under warranty, contact the manufacturer for repair. 7) Avoid repeatedly opening/closing the lid at extreme angles."},
    {"title": "Desktop PC not turning on at all", "description": "When I press the power button, nothing happens. No lights, no fan spinning, completely dead.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "Dead PC troubleshooting: 1) Check if the power cable is firmly connected and the outlet works (test with another device). 2) Check if the PSU switch on the back is turned ON (I side). 3) Try a different power cable. 4) Open the case and check for loose power connections to the motherboard (24-pin ATX and 4/8-pin CPU). 5) Perform a PSU paper clip test to check if the power supply is working. 6) Remove all components except CPU and one RAM stick, try booting. 7) Check for a blown capacitor on the motherboard (look for bulging or leaking caps). 8) Try a known working PSU if available."},
    {"title": "Overheating and thermal throttling", "description": "My laptop gets extremely hot during use and performance drops significantly. The fans are always running at full speed.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "Reduce overheating: 1) Clean the vents and fans using compressed air (power off first). 2) Use a laptop cooling pad or elevate the laptop for better airflow. 3) Check thermal paste condition - if the laptop is 3+ years old, it may need replacement. 4) Reduce CPU power: Power Options > Change plan settings > Change advanced > Processor power management > Maximum processor state > Set to 90-95%. 5) Monitor temperatures using HWMonitor or Core Temp. CPU should stay below 85°C. 6) Close background applications that use excessive CPU/GPU. 7) Ensure you're using the laptop on a hard, flat surface, not on a bed or pillow."},
    {"title": "Mouse cursor jumping erratically", "description": "My mouse cursor moves on its own and jumps to random positions on the screen. Very difficult to click anything.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "Fix erratic mouse: 1) For a wireless mouse: replace batteries/charge it. Check for wireless interference. 2) Try a different USB port for the receiver. 3) Clean the mouse sensor lens with a microfiber cloth. 4) Try the mouse on a different surface or use a mousepad. 5) For touchpad issues on laptops: disable the touchpad while using an external mouse (Settings > Devices > Touchpad). 6) Update mouse/touchpad drivers. 7) Check for electromagnetic interference from nearby devices. 8) Test with a different mouse to determine if it's a hardware issue. 9) Adjust mouse sensitivity: Settings > Devices > Mouse > Additional mouse options."},
    {"title": "Docking station not detecting monitors", "description": "My laptop docking station only shows one external monitor. It should support dual monitors.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "Docking station display fix: 1) Check dock firmware - visit manufacturer website for updates. 2) Update laptop's graphics drivers. 3) In Display Settings, click 'Detect'. 4) Try different cable types (some docks prefer DisplayPort over HDMI). 5) Check if your laptop supports DisplayPort MST (Multi-Stream Transport) for daisy-chaining. 6) Try connecting monitors directly to the laptop to verify they work. 7) Some docks require USB drivers - install the manufacturer's dock software. 8) Check power delivery - some docks need both data and power connections. 9) Try a different USB-C/Thunderbolt port on the laptop."},

    # ─── MORE TECHNICAL ───
    {"title": "Dual boot not showing startup menu", "description": "I installed Linux alongside Windows but the boot menu doesn't appear. It goes straight to Windows.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Fix dual boot menu: 1) In Windows, open Command Prompt as Admin and run 'bcdedit /set {bootmgr} displaybootmenu yes'. 2) Check UEFI/BIOS boot order - ensure the Linux boot loader (GRUB) is first. 3) For UEFI systems, use 'efibootmgr' from a Linux live USB to check boot entries. 4) Run 'bcdedit /set {bootmgr} timeout 10' to set a 10-second timeout. 5) Boot from Linux live USB and reinstall GRUB: 'sudo grub-install /dev/sda' and 'sudo update-grub'. 6) Check if Secure Boot is interfering - try disabling it in BIOS."},
    {"title": "Windows Update stuck at downloading", "description": "Windows Update has been stuck at '45% downloading' for the past 3 hours. It won't proceed or cancel.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Fix stuck Windows Update: 1) Stop the Windows Update service: Open Services (services.msc) > Windows Update > Stop. 2) Delete the update cache: Navigate to C:\\Windows\\SoftwareDistribution\\Download and delete all files. 3) Restart the Windows Update service. 4) Run the Windows Update Troubleshooter: Settings > Update & Security > Troubleshoot. 5) Try updating via the Microsoft Update Catalog (catalog.update.microsoft.com) manually. 6) Run 'DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth' then 'sfc /scannow'. 7) If on a metered connection, switch to unmetered. 8) Ensure at least 20GB of free disk space."},
    {"title": "Permission denied when accessing folder", "description": "Getting 'You don't have permission to access this folder' error when trying to open a folder on my own computer.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Fix folder permissions: 1) Right-click the folder > Properties > Security tab > Edit > Add your username and grant Full Control. 2) Take ownership: Properties > Security > Advanced > Owner > Change > Enter your username > Check 'Replace owner on subcontainers'. 3) Try running File Explorer as Administrator. 4) Open Command Prompt as Admin and run 'takeown /f \"folder_path\" /r /d y' followed by 'icacls \"folder_path\" /grant username:F /t'. 5) Check if the folder is encrypted (Properties > General > Advanced > Encrypt contents). 6) Boot into Safe Mode and try accessing the folder."},

    # ─── MORE NETWORK ───
    {"title": "DNS resolution failures", "description": "Getting 'DNS server not responding' for certain websites while others work fine.", "category": "network", "resolution": "DNS troubleshooting: 1) Flush DNS: Open Command Prompt as Admin, run 'ipconfig /flushdns'. 2) Change to public DNS: Open Network adapter properties > IPv4 > Use 8.8.8.8 (Google) or 1.1.1.1 (Cloudflare). 3) Test with 'nslookup domain.com 8.8.8.8' to check DNS resolution. 4) Reset DNS client: Run 'net stop dnscache' then 'net start dnscache'. 5) Check hosts file (C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts) for unexpected entries. 6) Disable IPv6 temporarily in adapter settings. 7) Run 'netsh int ip reset' to reset TCP/IP stack."},
    {"title": "Video calls keep buffering and lagging", "description": "Zoom and Teams calls have constant buffering and my video keeps freezing during meetings.", "category": "network", "resolution": "Improve video call quality: 1) Use a wired Ethernet connection instead of WiFi. 2) Close other bandwidth-heavy applications and browser tabs. 3) Lower video quality in call settings (720p instead of 1080p). 4) Check your internet speed - video calls need at least 3 Mbps upload. 5) Move closer to the WiFi router. 6) Disable HD video and virtual backgrounds in the app settings. 7) Check QoS (Quality of Service) settings on your router - prioritize video call traffic. 8) If on VPN, try disconnecting VPN for the call duration if allowed."},

    # ─── MORE BILLING ───
    {"title": "Unexpected price increase on renewal", "description": "My subscription renewed at a higher price than last year without any notice.", "category": "billing", "resolution": "Address price increase: 1) Check your email for any price change notifications (these may have gone to spam). 2) Review the terms of service regarding price adjustments. 3) Log into your account and check current plan pricing vs what was charged. 4) Contact billing support and ask about the price difference. 5) Ask about loyalty discounts or promotional pricing for existing customers. 6) Request to be notified in advance of any future price changes. 7) Consider downgrading to a lower tier if the price increase is significant. 8) Compare with competitors to negotiate a better rate."},

    # ─── MORE ACCOUNT ───
    {"title": "Single Sign-On SSO not working", "description": "Cannot log in using company SSO. Getting 'Authentication failed' error when trying to use my corporate credentials.", "category": "account", "resolution": "SSO troubleshooting: 1) Clear browser cache and cookies, especially for the identity provider domain. 2) Try incognito/private browsing mode. 3) Verify your corporate account is active (try logging into other corporate services). 4) Check if your organization recently changed SSO providers. 5) Try a different browser. 6) Check if your account has been provisioned for this specific application. 7) Verify the SSO URL is correct (not a phishing attempt). 8) Contact your IT administrator to check the SSO configuration and your account provisioning. 9) Check if MFA is required and ensure your MFA method is working."},

    # ─── MORE HARDWARE ───
    {"title": "External hard drive not detected", "description": "My external hard drive doesn't show up when I plug it in. It used to work before but now nothing happens.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "External drive detection fix: 1) Try a different USB port (preferably USB 3.0 on the back of the PC). 2) Try a different USB cable. 3) Check Disk Management (diskmgmt.msc) - the drive may appear but without a drive letter. 4) If visible without a letter, right-click > Change Drive Letter and Paths > Add. 5) If showing as RAW or unallocated, your data may still be recoverable with tools like TestDisk or Recuva. 6) Update USB drivers in Device Manager. 7) Check if the drive appears in BIOS. 8) Listen for spinning sounds - if completely silent, the drive or enclosure may be dead. 9) Try removing the drive from its enclosure and connecting directly via SATA."},
    {"title": "Keyboard key stuck or repeating", "description": "The 'A' key on my keyboard types multiple characters with a single press. Sometimes it won't stop repeating.", "category": "hardware", "resolution": "Fix repeating key: 1) Adjust key repeat settings: Settings > Accessibility > Keyboard > Check repeat delay and repeat rate. 2) Turn off Filter Keys: Settings > Accessibility > Keyboard > Filter Keys > Off. 3) For mechanical keyboards: remove the keycap and clean underneath with compressed air. 4) Check for liquid damage - if liquid was spilled, clean with isopropyl alcohol and let dry completely. 5) Try an external keyboard to rule out software issues. 6) Update keyboard driver. 7) For laptops, the keyboard ribbon cable might need reseating. 8) If it's a switch issue on a mechanical keyboard, the individual switch can be replaced."},

    # ─── MIXED/ADDITIONAL ───
    {"title": "Files disappeared from desktop", "description": "All my desktop files and folders have disappeared. The desktop is completely empty.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Recover desktop files: 1) Check if you're logged into the correct user account. 2) Right-click desktop > View > Show desktop icons (it might be toggled off). 3) Check if tablet mode is activated: Settings > System > Tablet. 4) Navigate to C:\\Users\\YourUsername\\Desktop to check if files are still there. 5) If using OneDrive, check if desktop sync moved your files: OneDrive Settings > Backup > Manage backup. 6) Check Recycle Bin for accidentally deleted files. 7) Check if a recent Windows update changed your profile path. 8) Run a file recovery tool like Recuva if files were truly deleted."},
    {"title": "Outlook calendar not syncing", "description": "My Outlook calendar events are not syncing with my phone and the web version shows different events than the desktop app.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Calendar sync fix: 1) In Outlook desktop, go to File > Account Settings > ensure the correct account is set as default. 2) Try Send/Receive All Folders (F9). 3) Check if you're viewing the correct calendar - you may have multiple calendars. 4) In Outlook.com, verify events are in the correct calendar folder. 5) On your phone, remove and re-add the account. 6) Check sync settings: Go to Calendar permissions and sharing settings. 7) Create a new Outlook profile if the issue persists: Control Panel > Mail > Show Profiles > Add. 8) Clear the local Outlook cache: Close Outlook, delete .ost file from AppData\\Local\\Microsoft\\Outlook."},
    {"title": "Background apps using too much memory", "description": "My computer is always at 90%+ memory usage. Task Manager shows several background apps consuming large amounts of RAM.", "category": "technical", "resolution": "Reduce memory usage: 1) Open Task Manager > Processes tab > sort by Memory > end unnecessary processes. 2) Startup tab > disable apps you don't need at startup. 3) Check for memory leaks: if a process keeps growing in memory, restart it or the app. 4) Uninstall apps you no longer use: Settings > Apps. 5) Disable unnecessary Windows services: services.msc. 6) Adjust visual effects: System Properties > Advanced > Performance Settings > Adjust for best performance. 7) Consider upgrading RAM if consistently at high usage. 8) Check for malware with a full system scan."},
    {"title": "Cloud storage sync conflicts", "description": "OneDrive keeps showing sync conflicts and creating duplicate files with '(1)' appended.", "category": "software", "resolution": "OneDrive sync conflict resolution: 1) Check the OneDrive icon in the taskbar for sync status and errors. 2) Click on conflicting files to choose which version to keep. 3) Pause sync, resolve conflicts manually, then resume. 4) Check if the same file was edited on multiple devices simultaneously. 5) OneDrive Settings > Account > Unlink this PC, then re-link. 6) Reset OneDrive: Win+R > 'wsreset.exe' and '%localappdata%\\Microsoft\\OneDrive\\onedrive.exe /reset'. 7) Ensure file names don't contain special characters or exceed path length limits (260 chars)."},
    {"title": "Data recovery after accidental deletion", "description": "I accidentally permanently deleted important files (Shift+Delete). They're not in the Recycle Bin.", "category": "software", "resolution": "Data recovery steps: 1) STOP using the drive immediately to prevent overwriting. 2) Try Previous Versions: right-click the folder > Properties > Previous Versions. 3) Check if File History is enabled: Settings > Update & Security > Backup. 4) Check cloud storage (OneDrive, Google Drive) for synced copies. 5) Use Recuva (free) for basic recovery: install on a DIFFERENT drive than the one with deleted files. 6) For important data, use professional tools like R-Studio or EaseUS. 7) If the files are critical, consider professional data recovery services. 8) In the future, enable File History and cloud backup for important folders."},
    {"title": "New employee onboarding - system access", "description": "I'm a new employee and I don't have access to any internal systems. I need email, VPN, and shared drives set up.", "category": "account", "resolution": "New employee access setup: 1) Contact your IT department or help desk with your employee ID and manager's name. 2) You should have received an IT onboarding email - check your personal email. 3) For corporate email: your IT admin needs to create your account in Azure AD/Google Workspace. 4) VPN access: request VPN credentials and client software from IT. 5) Shared drives: your manager needs to request access through the appropriate approval workflow. 6) Standard onboarding takes 1-2 business days for basic access. 7) You'll likely need to set up MFA (authenticator app) for all corporate accounts. 8) Ask your manager to submit an access request ticket if not already done."},
]
